		<content translate="true">&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Discussion Topic&lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Itâ€™s important for parents to recognize what is developmentally appropriate for different age groups. &lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Match the following exploration activities with the appropriate age group.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Sample Activities&lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;LI&gt;I like to explore my world, but I always check to make sure my mom is close by. (Toddler)&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;I keep throwing the spoon to the floor to learn about cause and effect. (Infant)&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;LI&gt;I ask, "Why?" so that I can understand the rules and what you want me to do. (Preschooler)&lt;/LI&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Sample Feedback&lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;Children continue to grow and develop explore as they explore. When parents and caregivers understand how young children use exploration to learn, they are able to nurture and encourage their children's learning.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;B&gt;Discussion Question&lt;/B&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;What are examples of safe ways that parents can encourage exploration?&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P ALIGN="LEFT"&gt;&lt;/P&gt;</content>
	</text>
